stadiums.name: Moulay Abdellah Stadium
stadiums.description: Moulay Abdellah Stadium, located in Rabat, Morocco, is a major multi-purpose venue with a capacity of approximately 52,000 spectators. Primarily used for football matches, it also hosts athletics events and cultural activities. Renovated ahead of the 2014 Club World Cup, the stadium features modern amenities and improved facilities. Named after Prince Moulay Abdellah, it holds historical significance as a host of international sporting events and large public gatherings. The stadium symbolizes national pride and serves as a key hub for sports and culture in Morocco.

stadiums.name: Mohamed V Stadium
stadiums.description: Mohamed V Stadium, located in Casablanca, is Morocco's largest stadium with a capacity of approximately 67,000 spectators. Primarily used for football, it is home to the popular clubs Raja and Wydad Casablanca and has hosted major events like the African Cup of Nations and FIFA World Cup qualifiers. Renovated for the 2000 African Cup of Nations, it features modern facilities and improved infrastructure. Beyond sports, the stadium is a symbol of national pride and hosts concerts and cultural events. Known for its vibrant atmosphere, it remains a key hub for sports and entertainment in Morocco.

stadiums.name: Grand Tangier Stadium
stadiums.description: Grand Tangier Stadium , inaugurated in 2011, is a modern multi-purpose venue with a capacity of 45,000 spectators. Located in Tangier, it hosts football matches, concerts, and major events, including games for IR Tanger and the Moroccan national team. Equipped with advanced facilities like a retractable roof, it meets international standards for FIFA and UEFA competitions. The stadium played a key role in the 2018 African Nations Championship (CHAN). Beyond sports, it is a cultural landmark, symbolizing Tangier's emergence as a global city.

stadiums.name: Grand Marrakech Stadium
stadiums.description: Grand Marrakech Stadium , inaugurated in 2011, is a state-of-the-art venue with a capacity of 45,000 spectators. Located in Marrakech, it hosts football matches, including games for Kawkab Marrakech and the Moroccan national team, as well as major events like the 2013 FIFA Club World Cup and 2018 CHAN. Equipped with modern facilities, it meets international standards for sports and entertainment. Beyond football, the stadium is a cultural landmark, hosting concerts and events that highlight Marrakech's global appeal. Its sleek design and strategic location make it a key venue for sports and culture in Morocco.

stadiums.name: Grand Agadir Stadium
stadiums.description: Grand Agadir Stadium , inaugurated in 2011, is a modern venue with a capacity of 45,000 spectators, located in Agadir, Morocco. Primarily used for football, it serves as the home ground for Hassania Agadir and hosts matches for the Moroccan national team. Equipped with advanced facilities, it meets international standards and has hosted major events like FIFA World Cup qualifiers and AFCON matches. Beyond sports, the stadium hosts concerts and cultural events, contributing to Agadir's reputation as a dynamic city. Its modern design and coastal location make it a key landmark for sports and entertainment in southern Morocco.

stadiums.name: Fes Stadium
stadiums.description: Fes Stadium , inaugurated in 2008, is a modern venue with a capacity of 45,000 spectators, located in Fez, Morocco. Primarily used for football, it serves as the home ground for Maghreb de Fès and hosts matches for the Moroccan national team. Equipped with advanced facilities, it meets international standards and has hosted major events like FIFA World Cup qualifiers and AFCON matches. Beyond sports, the stadium hosts concerts and cultural events, contributing to Fez's reputation as a vibrant city. Its location near historical landmarks makes it a key sports and entertainment hub in Morocco.

stadiums.name: Moulay Hassan Stadium
stadiums.description: Moulay Hassan Stadium , built in 1923, is one of Morocco's oldest stadiums, located in Rabat with a capacity of 12,000–15,000 spectators. Primarily used for football, it serves as the home ground for AS FAR and hosts local sporting events. Though modest in size and facilities, it holds significant historical and cultural value. Known for its intimate atmosphere and nostalgic charm, it remains a beloved venue for football fans. Its central location in Rabat makes it a key part of the city's sporting heritage.

stadiums.name: Barid Stadium
stadiums.description: Barid Stadium , built in the 1940s, is a historic venue in Casablanca with a capacity of 10,000–15,000 spectators. Once associated with Raja Casablanca, it played a key role in the growth of football in Morocco. Though modest in size and facilities, it holds cultural significance as a symbol of grassroots sports. The stadium is cherished for its nostalgic charm and intimate atmosphere. Today, it hosts lower-tier matches and remains a part of Casablanca's sporting heritage.

stadiums.name: Olympic Moulay Abdellah Stadium
stadiums.description: Olympic Moulay Abdellah Stadium , located in Rabat, is a multi-purpose sports complex with a capacity of 52,000 spectators. Originally built in 1959, it was modernized for the 2014 FIFA Club World Cup and now meets international standards. The venue hosts football matches, athletics events, concerts, and cultural gatherings. It played a key role in the 2019 African Games and serves as a symbol of Morocco's sporting excellence. Its state-of-the-art facilities and central location make it a cornerstone of sports and entertainment in the country.
